### Using Machine Learning for Early Identification of Non-Optimal Manufacturing Conditions

Rahim Merchant

#### Manufacturing organizations rely on stable operating conditions to maintain equipment reliability, production efficiency, and product quality. The goal of this project is to determine whether machine learning can be used to identify non-optimal operating conditions using machine and process-related data.

Using the AI4I 2020 Predictive Maintenance Dataset, exploratory data analysis (EDA) was performed to better understand the relationships between key operating variables. Logistic Regression and K-Nearest Neighbours (KNN) were then used as baseline classification models.

Initial results show that machine learning can be used to identify non-optimal operating conditions. While both models performed well overall, KNN was more effective at identifying failure-related conditions and may provide a stronger foundation for future analysis.

#### Rationale
In manufacturing environments, equipment reliability has a direct impact on safety, production output, maintenance costs, and overall business performance. When operating conditions become non-optimal, organizations often experience unplanned downtime, reduced equipment performance, and increased maintenance activity.

As a Reliability Engineer, a significant part of the role involves identifying potential issues before they impact production. The ability to use machine and process data to predict non-optimal operating conditions could help organizations make more proactive maintenance and operational decisions.

#### Research Question
Can machine learning be used to predict whether manufacturing operating conditions are optimal or non-optimal based on machine and process-related variables?

#### Data Sources
This project uses the AI4I 2020 Predictive Maintenance Dataset obtained from Kaggle.

https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/stephanmatzka/predictive-maintenance-dataset-ai4i-2020

The dataset contains machine and process-related variables including:

Machine type
Air temperature
Process temperature
Rotational speed
Torque
Tool wear
Machine failure information

These variables provide a useful representation of operating conditions commonly monitored in manufacturing environments.

#### Methodology
The analysis began with data cleaning and exploratory data analysis (EDA). The dataset was reviewed for missing values and duplicate records before being prepared for modelling. Machine type was converted into numerical variables using one-hot encoding to allow it to be used by machine learning algorithms.

Several visualizations were created to better understand the data, including histograms, box plots, and scatterplots. These visualizations helped identify trends, distributions, and potential outliers within the dataset.

Two classification models were developed:

Logistic Regression
K-Nearest Neighbours (KNN)

Model performance was evaluated using accuracy, precision, recall, F1-score, and confusion matrices.

#### Results
The dataset was found to contain no missing values or duplicate records. Exploratory data analysis showed a strong relationship between air temperature and process temperature, while variables such as rotational speed, torque, and tool wear demonstrated greater variability across operating conditions.

A Logistic Regression model achieved an accuracy of 96.75%. However, further evaluation showed that the model struggled to identify non-optimal operating conditions and missed a large number of failure observations.

A K-Nearest Neighbours (KNN) model achieved an accuracy of 97.40% and was more effective at identifying failure-related operating conditions. Based on the initial results, KNN appears to be the stronger model for this dataset.

These findings suggest that machine learning can be used to identify non-optimal operating conditions using machine and process-related variables and may support more proactive reliability and maintenance decision-making.

#### Next steps
The focus will be on improving model performance and comparing additional machine learning techniques. Further analysis will also be performed to better understand which operating variables have the greatest impact on non-optimal conditions.

The long-term goal is to develop insights that could help Reliability Engineers, Maintenance Teams, and Operations personnel identify issues earlier and reduce the risk of unplanned downtime.

